Worth noting one of their three 10%+ customers is in", "id_str": "2077168088538313061", "in_reply_to_screen_name": "Sam_Badawi", "in_reply_to_status_id_str": "2077167369898877366", "in_reply_to_user_id_str": "1241543417093451776", "is_quote_status": false, "lang": "en", "quote_count": 0, "reply_count": 0, "retweet_count": 0, "retweeted": false, "user_id_str": "2070660294645612544"}, "note_tweet": {"is_expandable": true, "note_tweet_results": {"result": {"entity_set": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "id": "Tm90ZVR3ZWV0OjIwNzcxNjgwODg0NjcwMDU0NDA=", "text": "The mix shift under that bar is the real story. Two years ago 95% of AEHR was silicon carbide for EVs. Last quarter AI processors and silicon photonics were over 80% of revenue, up from 56%. Same company, different end market.

Worth noting one of their three 10%+ customers is in optical transceivers. Burn-in is upstream of the transceiver, which is upstream of the switch. When you see AOI breaking ground on 400,000 square feet the same week this backlog prints, you’re looking at one demand signal showing up at two points on the same line."}}}, "rest_id": "2077168088538313061", "source": "<a href="http://twitter.com/download/iphone" rel="nofollow">Twitter for iPhone</a>", "unmention_data": {}, "views": {"count": "38", "state": "EnabledWithCount"}}

